node.text:
Today we took in a new foster kitten! Spud is a tiny kitten the size & development of a 5-7 day old, but if you can believe this…he’s actually 16 days old! He was born very prematurely when his mama, a feral cat, came into our local TNR clinic @feral_cat_coalition in a trap. He was the only kitten born, and his mama was not able to care for him, so he was raised for the past two weeks by the clinic manager, @aud_everything_is_taken. Audrey reached out and asked if we had any interest in taking him on, and of course, we said HECK YES!

His former foster name was Bruno, but since we have already raised a baby Bruno, we collectively decided to name him after what he looks like most — a chonky potato. As you can see, he has an incredible appetite and a rotund belly! Audrey, you did a beautiful job getting him through his most vulnerable weeks, and I’m so happy we can help carry the baton from here to adoption.

Welcome, Spud Spudley! We love you!🥔

node.text:
I was so nervous about this! I wasn’t sure if Pearl would follow us on a walk or if she would run loose on our property! I needed to get her from our building to a fenced yard, and took a chance to see if she could responsibly go on a walk. She did a great job! PHEW!

Jojo is still recovering from her spay, so we are going to give the pigs another day or two apart to avoid any further #pigdrama 🐷

Thanks @dvniwhitten for helping this morning!

The ‘doos are all becoming big fans of affection now, and almost every one of them has started loving having their tummies rubbed. Here are just a few clips of Bennie, Dustie, Reggie, Sadie, and Stevie!

Most of our piglets have adopters now, which is so exciting! Bennie and Reggie are two who don’t have a home lined up just yet, and as you can see they are both huge sweethearts. I know their person is out there! If you think you might make a great loving pig adopter, are properly zoned, and live anywhere on the west coast, we would love to hear from you. Reach out via our adoption app at orphankittenclub.org/adopt ♥️

node.text:
I had the cutest morning ever — teaching a virtual children’s class (with the help of Charolette the kitten!) I got up bright and early to chat with elementary school boys in Baltimore about different ways to help cats, and it was truly heartwarming. Children are so naturally inquisitive and compassionate, and I love when teachers and guardians give them opportunities to learn about animal welfare! ♥️

If you’re looking for resources for cat-loving kids, I have a children’s book called “Kitten Lady’s Big Book of Little Kittens” (reading level: 4-8, but anyone can enjoy it!) My book shares fun and exciting information all about kitten care and fostering, and it even includes a bunch of ideas for kids who want to help cats! You can find it at your local bookstore, your favorite online book shop, or at KittenLady.org/books 📖

node.text:
Watch out, world—here comes Merriam! Choo choo! All aboard the hot mess express! 🚂🔥😝

Why oh why is she always covered in food, you ask? Great question. It’s because…she’s a food-sucker!

A common danger of working with weaning-age kittens is that at mealtime, they often look like they’re eating…when in reality they are just sucking the food & getting very little of it in their mouth (and often a lot of it on their face.) This is dangerous because if you don’t realize what’s going on, they can end up going hungry. That’s why it’s important to observe kittens closely & weigh them at least once daily (preferably more!)

Some tell tale signs that Merriam is a food-sucker:

1) She always has food on her face
2) She isn’t appropriately gaining weight
3) She spends a disproportionately long amount of time at the food dish, but the quantity of food doesn’t decrease
4) When you watch her eat, you can see that she’s making nursing motions with her mouth rather than biting/chewing

It’s common for people to look at a kitten who is hovering over a dish and making mouth-sounds to assume that the kitten is eating great, but in reality they may be crying out for help! In cases like this, it’s best to either scale back to a bottle, or to do assisted spoon feeding or hand feeding until you are confident that the kitten can eat on her own. You can also switch to a more lickable food, like a mousse, which can be a little easier for kittens like this to figure out!

Now that Merriam is spoon feeding, she is gaining weight and getting a nice chonky bellbell. 😋

You can learn a TON about weaning in my free webinar “Beyond the Bottle” at kittenlady.org/webinar

Fergie is doing better today. He’s not 100%, but it seems like the antibiotics are kicking in & he is rallying. In the past, when he has dealt with acute infections, it’s taken many days for him to recover, so I know not to expect him to be his usual self right away…but I sure hope we get that playful boy back soon!

I’m coping with all this by putting together all the fun toys & enrichment everyone has been sending to him (thank you so much.) I truly think it is helping me as much as it is helping him. To be able to create a Fergie Fun Room makes it feel so joyful, and he is loving checking out all of his soft beds & cool climbers! He is even playing with some of the little plush toys today, which gives me hope that he is feeling happier by the minute. 💕 #chimpytender

Please keep Fergie in your thoughts. He is struggling tonight.

Today we noticed he was a little more sleepy than usual, and his appetite was a little worse. Then, a few hours ago, I went to take this video and noticed at the end that he seemed to be trembling. Hmm. Trembling is commonly associated with fevers, so I took his temperature just to be sure he was okay…and it was 104.5.

Ugh. 😭

I called our vet in tears. She said that a fever isn’t a normal part of kidney failure, but is more likely a sign of kidney infection (which his kidney disease makes him very vulnerable to.) It’s terrible news, but the only positive thing is that with quick intervention, it is possible that we could get him back on track.

You might remember that every time he goes off antibiotics, he becomes critically ill. He has been on 3 antibiotics for almost his entire life, and whenever we try to take him off of them, his health quickly deteriorates. Well, his nephrologist really wanted him to go off 2 of the 3, so one week ago we did that. And it seemed like it was going okay. Until tonight.

So now he is back on everything, and if he survives this, he will probably need to stay on this protocol for the rest of his life. His kidney condition makes him very vulnerable to infection and it seems that he cannot tolerate being off of any of the antibiotics he has been on throughout his life.

He has survived these acute battles 3 times now and I hope this will be a 4th. I hope I caught this with enough time for us to turn it around. I hope that a few days from now he will be back to playing and pouncing on Haroun. But in the meantime I am devastated and very worried. I just hope we have more time.

This is so hard. 😔 #chimpytender

Have you ever seen the SNL skit of The Lawrence Welk Show with the four singing sisters? Three are traditionally beautiful and sing about “normal” interests, like rainbows and butterflies, and the fourth sister has a receding hairline and tiny hands, and sings about strange things like chasing cars. If you haven’t seen it, then I’m sure this post makes no sense to you, but basically—our new clubhouse kittens remind me of that skit. 😝

Charolette is a gorgeous brown tabby girl with a sweet, spunky personality and a fiery passion for treats.

Tyndall is a stunning, fluffy black and white tuxedo boy with big paws and an even bigger purr when you cuddle him.

Merriam is a crusty, tiny space alien 
with little legs and…an inexplicable bald spot on her head.

She cracks me UP! Don’t worry—this crew has been in quarantine with one of our volunteers for weeks, and Merriam has been tested and cleared for pretty much every skin condition. Her fur is growing back in, but in the meantime, she just has this very silly bald spot. Obviously, we love all kittens, but there is something extra lovable about an oddball…and that’s definitely Merriam!

These three will soon be adoptable through @orphankittenclub!

Thank you to our volunteer @saratoga_cat_sanctuary for caring for them these past few weeks!

“Help! I’m stuck! How do I turn this wacky thing off?!” - Daisy Gold at her morning feeding 😝😝😝

Every once in a while, a kitten will continue suckling even after they have unlatched from the nipple. When this happens, I call it “getting stuck,” and it cracks me up every time! Suckling is one of the strongest instincts a kitten has — from the moment they’re born they instinctively know how to do it — so it makes sense that they occasionally space out and their tongue goes on autopilot. ♥️
